Kernel Density Estimation¶

In this project, we will use a psychological experiment dataset to study whether or not the two brain regions are likely to be independent of each other and considering different types of political view For this question; The data set \textsf{n90pol.csv} contains information on 90 university students who participated in a psychological experiment designed to look for relationships between the size of different regions of the brain and political views. The variables amygdala and acc indicate the volume of two particular brain regions known to be involved in emotions and decision-making, the amygdala and the anterior cingulate cortex; more exactly, these are residuals from the predicted volume, after adjusting for height, sex, and similar body-type variables. The variable \textsf{orientation} gives the students' locations on a five-point scale from 1 (very conservative) to 5 (very liberal). Note that in the dataset, we only have observations for orientation from 2 to 5.

We begin by loading in all of our necessary packages as well as the dataset which we will display a preview of below:

Interactive Amygdala Histogram:¶

Next, we plot each of the non-label features in the dataset via a 1D histogram to get a better understanding of the distribution of each feature’s data. The histogram methodology has some flexibility in how to choose the number of bins, I have supplied interactive charts below that use sliders to update the plots to your chosen number of bins to display. By default, each plot is set at the number of bins I found most intuitive for observing the plots. These plots are listed below along with some other static charts of other intersecting values of bandwidth:

def amygdala_hist(Bins):
    plt.hist(amygdala,density=True,label='Histogram',edgecolor='#1f77b4',bins=Bins,color='w')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.xlabel('%s Bins'% Bins)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('Histogram of Amygdala Data')
widgets.interact(amygdala_hist,Bins=(2,20))
plt.show()

The Plot above displays a visualization of the Amygdala dataset feature plotted along 11 histogram bins. After playing with various bin values, I arrived at 11 as the final choice as this in my opinion represents a good parameterization structure of the distribution. As we can see the chart shows a distinct mean, but not quite symmetric structure given the large left tail.

The above static charts of Amygdala histograms with varying bin numbers allow us to understand the data a bit more. As we can see under bin 5, the distribution seems very approachable and nearly normal aside from a slight skewness. However, it is important to acknowledge that although this is a nice smoother representation of the data, the low number of bins causes us to lose valuable information on the distribution of data by grouping our data in broader buckets. Moving onto the 7-bin chart we see a slightly jumpier structure of the 5-bin example. This makes a good representation as it captures more of the data's structure while keeping all bins populated (a main challenge of increasing bin numbers). The distribution still displays the skewness as displayed in the 5-bin example. Next, we move onto the 11-bin example. Under the 11-bin approach we can see our mean is much more defined with respect to the other data. Additionally, we have been able to fill all buckets thus making the discrete representation of the data's distribution somewhat less disjoint. However, it is notable that our first bin in this model demonstrates very high frequency for a grouping that should (in theory under a normal gaussian) fall into the left tail and thus be far less frequent. Of further interest is how our prior graphs had this same skewness, but the causes of which were largely hidden until we expanded enough bins to see that far left values isolated in the extreme low of the data were causing the skewness and they were in fact not more equally distributed among the left side of the distribution. For this reason, I chose to select 11 bins as our optimal representation. Additionally, as we see for our final chart in the 14-bin case that at this level of bins we fail to attain non-empty bins. Next, we move onto the next non-label feature in the dataset the Anterior Cingulate Cortex Volume known referred to further on as "Acc".

The above plots consider various parameterizations of the histogram bins value. The comparison of each plot follows similar observations to those explained in the amygdala histogram. We see that with our lowest bin values such as 6 in the case of Acc our data is too smooth and hides too much structure to be of value for analysis. However, as we move to higher values of bins such as 12 and more specifically 15 we see that the visualization becomes too noisy and in the case of 15 bins specifically, disjoined with empty bins. This could demonstrate that there is a deeper relationship behind these similar distribution shapes, but such an assertion would require more analysis with rigor beyond a simple histogram plot. We will explore such alternate methods in the analysis below beginning with Kernel Density Estimation.

Amygdala Gaussian Kernel Density Estimator:¶

With each our 1-D histograms plotted above; we can now move on an alternate more flexible approach for observing our data's distributional properties using the KDE method of density estimation. These output plots are displayed below beginning with an interactive KDE chart with user defined bandwidth parameterization initialized at the recommended Silverman bandwidth, and followed by static plots of various interesting values of bandwidth each visualized side-by-side for direct comparison:

In [7]:
def amygdala_kde_single(bandwidth):
    sns.kdeplot(sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amygdala),bw=bandwidth,shade=True)
    plt.title('Amygdala Gaussian KDE with Bandwidth = %s'%bandwidth)
    plt.ylabel('Density')
    plt.xlabel('Scaled Anygdala Values')
widgets.interact(amygdala_kde_single, bandwidth=widgets.FloatSlider(min=.01,max=1.0,step=0.01, value=round(scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amygdala),bw_method='silverman').factor,2)))
plt.show()

The above chart displays the Gaussian Kernel Density Estimates for the Amygdala feature. However, unlike the prior histogram (discrete) view of the data, the KDE approach uses a continuous approach to give us a parametric equivalent pdf bootstrapped from the data. This approach allows us to better understand the properties of our distribution and makes for better visualization. KDE like our prior histograms requires parameterization, but instead of bins we will be concerned with bandwidth. In this case bandwidth determines how much weight we will give to each individual gaussian kernel placed on each data point. If we choose a value of bandwidth too small, it will result in very erratic and unusual visualization. However, on the other hand, if we choose our bandwidth to be too large, we will approach a more squished normal shape which prevents any sort of unique analysis (in a way to opposite relationship observed with decreasing and increasing bandwidth values). Compromising between these two ranges of extremes we arrive at 0.43 as a good value for amygdala bandwidth that preserves some of the data's unique structure without becoming too discontinuous. In analyzing the plot, it is notable that we have great gaussian structure aside from the lumped values around deviations negative two and negative one. We also note that the graph highly resembles our histogram choice for amygdala discussed above. The value of 0.43 selected for bandwidth is also the recommended value of bandwidth derived from the Silverman method which is one of two approaches for using mathematics to derive optimal bandwidth values (the other is Scott's method which is shown in static plots below).

As we can see from the above static plots, the chosen value of bandwidth is inherently important to KDE implementation. We notice in the first plot that the smallest value of bandwidth 0.10 demonstrates far too much discontinuity and noise to be helpful in analysis. This model is too mightily parametrized on individual observations and fails to capture the big picture of the data's behavior. On the alternate extreme, our last plot with bandwidth value of 1.0 we see the chart is far too like a normal gaussian and demonstrates over fitting. For these reasons we focus on the middle two plots of Silverman's and Scott's bandwidth equal to .41 and .43 respectively. Since the value both do a good job at representing the data, we will opt for the Silverman value as the industry default parameterization of KDE as our optimal value of bandwidth. 3D Histogram Plot for Joint Distribution of Amygdala and Acc:¶

In [11]:
def histogram_3d(bins):   
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(9,9))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
    x = amygdala
    y = acc
    abs_min = min(np.min(amygdala),np.min(acc))
    abs_max = max(np.max(amygdala),np.max(acc))
    increment = (abs_max - abs_min) / bins
    bound_list = [abs_min,abs_max]
    range_array = np.reshape(np.repeat(np.array(bound_list),2),(2,2)).T
    hist, xedges, yedges = np.histogram2d(x,y, bins=bins,range=[[-0.0676,0.0812], [-0.0676,0.0812]])
    xpos, ypos = np.meshgrid(xedges[:-1] + increment, yedges[:-1]+increment)
    xpos = xpos.ravel()
    ypos = ypos.ravel()
    zpos = 0
    dx = dy = increment * np.ones_like(zpos)
    dz = hist.ravel()
    cmap = cm.get_cmap('coolwarm') 
    max_height = np.max(dz)
    min_height = np.min(dz)
    rgba = [cmap((k-min_height)/max_height) for k in dz] 
    ax.bar3d(xpos, ypos, zpos, dx, dy, dz,color=rgba,shade=True)
    ax.set_title('3D Histogram for Amygdala and Acc')
    ax.set_zlabel('Frequency')
    ax.set_xlabel('Acc')
    ax.set_ylabel('Amygdala')
    plt.show()
interactive_plot_h = interactive(histogram_3d,bins=widgets.IntSlider(min=3, max=20, step=1, value=10))    
output_h = interactive_plot_h.children[-1]
output_h.layout.height = '520px'
interactive_plot_h

The initial value displayed (in the interactive chart) of 12 bins is the level at which I found the most relatable structure for the data. As we can see from the plot, there seems to be a strong visible mean, however it is flanked to the back left by a group of reasonably frequent occurrences whereas to the right and front frequency declines rapidly. This may suggest multi-modal data and will need to be examined further. However, this slight indication alone should probably begin to make a case that the data has some correlation and are both not independent nor jointly normal. xpos, ypos = np.meshgrid(xedges[:-1] + increment, yedges[:-1]+increment)
xpos = xpos.ravel()
ypos = ypos.ravel()
zpos = 0
dx = dy = increment * np.ones_like(zpos)
dz = hist.ravel()
cmap = cm.get_cmap('coolwarm') 
max_height = np.max(dz)
min_height = np.min(dz)
rgba = [cmap((k-min_height)/max_height) for k in dz] 
axs3.bar3d(xpos, ypos, zpos, dx, dy, dz,color=rgba,shade=True)
axs3.set_title('3D Histogram for Amygdala and Acc 15 Bins')
axs3.set_zlabel('Frequency')
axs3.set_xlabel('Acc')
axs3.set_ylabel('Amygdala')

plt.show()

The above 3D plots of varying bin width demonstrate the continued requirement of a good parameterization for histogram bootstrapping a distribution. In the 2D case we were concerned primarily with continuity and the presence of empty bins. However, in the 3D unscaled cases above we see that having our plot as a cube and given the shape of the data requires empty bins in the plot in all cases. The 3D case should be evaluated more on the basis of having few empty bins in the heart of the data cloud and accept empty bins so long as they fall on the cube's fringes. As we can see from the plots above evaluating on these guidelines it is probably quite clear that the latter two cases of bins = 12 and 15 are our best cases for parameterization of the histogram. In the initial two plots we see that our data is too closely structured to gain any real insight. However, in the latter 2 cases, we can clearly see the prevalence of multiple means/modes within the data which suggests our joint distribution of the data we have bootstrapped does not follow properties of independence.

3-Dimensional KDE Plot for Amygdala vs. ACC:¶

Just as we used KDE smooth curves to contrast the rigidity of discrete histograms, we can also apply this same transformation to both feature vector simultaneously in the 3D visualization case for the joint density of Amygdala and Acc features. However, it is notable that by playing around with various values of bandwidth we see quite interesting behavior from the distribution. Depending on how low we tune the parameter, we can start to see the emergence of three distinct peaks within the surface plot. This would indicate that our data has some not so independent properties.

##Axes might be swaped label wise check that before submission
def surface_plot_kde(bandwidth):
    data = np.copy(dual_array)
    data = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(data)
    abs_min = np.min(np.min(data,axis=0))
    abs_max = np.max(np.max(data,axis=0))
    grid_boxes = 50
    increments = (abs_max - abs_min) / grid_boxes
    grid_x, grid_y = np.meshgrid(np.arange(abs_min-increments*2,abs_max+increments*2,increments),np.arange(abs_min-increments*2,abs_max+increments*2,increments))
    grid_merged = (np.asarray([grid_x.flatten(order='F'),grid_y.flatten(order='F')])).T
    num_coords, cord_dims = grid_merged.shape
    m,n = data.shape
    data_normed = (np.power(data, 2)).sum(axis=1)
    h = bandwidth
    grid_normed = (np.power(grid_merged, 2)).sum(axis=1)
    cross = np.dot(data,grid_merged.T)
    kern_input0 = np.repeat(data_normed, repeats =num_coords).reshape((len(data_normed), num_coords))+np.tile(grid_normed, m).reshape((len(data_normed), num_coords)) - 2*cross
    kern_input = np.divide(kern_input0,(2*(h**2)))
    kern_output = (1/(2*math.pi)) * np.exp(-kern_input)
    mesh_kde = (((sum(kern_output) / ((m*h**n))).T).reshape(grid_x.shape[0],grid_y.shape[1])).T
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    ax=fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
    ax.set_title('Gaussian Kernel Density Estimator for Amygdala and Acc with Bandwidth = %s'%bandwidth)
    ax.set_zlabel('Density')
    ax.set_xlabel('Acc Normalized')
    ax.set_ylabel('Amygdala Normalized')
    surface = ax.plot_surface(grid_x, grid_y, mesh_kde,cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    fig.colorbar(surface,shrink=0.5)
    plt.show()
interactive_plot = interactive(surface_plot_kde,bandwidth=widgets.FloatSlider(min=0.001, max=1, step=0.001, value=0.50))    
output = interactive_plot.children[-1]
output.layout.height = '500px'
interactive_plot

def marginal_contour(bandwidth):

def joint_contour(bandwidth):
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    amy_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amygdala)
    acc_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(acc)
    amy_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(amy_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    acc_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(acc_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    amy_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(amy_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    acc_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(acc_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    joint_density = np.dot(acc_kde_density[:,np.newaxis],amy_kde_density[:,np.newaxis].T)
    plt.contourf(countour_grid,countour_grid,joint_density,cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    plt.title('Joint Probablity Density Map of P(Amygdala)P(Acc)')
    plt.ylabel('Acc Normalized')
    plt.xlabel('Amygdala Normalized')
    plt.colorbar(shrink=.5)

Probability Density Error Map of Amygdala and Acc:¶

Now here is where the real insight can be obtained, we can now compare the absolute difference between the conditional and joint distributions obtained above in order to assess their independence. If the distributions are in-fact independent then, we should see minimal strong disturbances in the error plot.

amy_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amygdala)

def error_plot_reg(bandwidth):
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    x_mesh,y_mesh = np.meshgrid(countour_grid,countour_grid)
    pos = np.vstack([x_mesh.ravel(),y_mesh.ravel()])
    joint_data = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(dual_array).T
    marginal_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(joint_data,bw_method=bandwidth)
    marginal_density = np.reshape(scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(marginal_kde_obj,pos),(countour_grid.shape[0],countour_grid.shape[0]))
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    amy_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amygdala)
    acc_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(acc)
    amy_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(amy_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    acc_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(acc_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    amy_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(amy_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    acc_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(acc_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    joint_density = np.dot(acc_kde_density[:,np.newaxis],amy_kde_density[:,np.newaxis].T)
    error_density = np.absolute(marginal_density - joint_density)
    plt.contourf(countour_grid,countour_grid,error_density,cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    plt.title('Error Density Map of P(Amygdala,Acc) vs. P(Amygdala)P(Acc)')
    plt.ylabel('Acc Normalized')
    plt.xlabel('Amygdala Normalized')
    plt.colorbar(shrink=.5)
widgets.interact(error_plot_reg, bandwidth=widgets.FloatSlider(min=.001,max=1.0,step=0.01,value=scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(amy_joint,bw_method='silverman').factor))

def conditioned_marginal_contour(bandwidth,C):
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    x_mesh,y_mesh = np.meshgrid(countour_grid,countour_grid)
    pos = np.vstack([x_mesh.ravel(),y_mesh.ravel()])
    conditioned_array = dual_array[np.where(orientation == C)[0],:]
    marginal_data_conditioned = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(conditioned_array).T
    marginal_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(marginal_data_conditioned,bw_method=bandwidth)
    marginal_density = np.reshape(scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(marginal_kde_obj,pos),(countour_grid.shape[0],countour_grid.shape[0]))
    plt.contourf(countour_grid,countour_grid,marginal_density,cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    plt.title('Marginal Density Map Conditioned on Orientation = %s'%C)
    plt.ylabel('Acc Normalized')
    plt.xlabel('Amygdala Normalized')
    plt.colorbar(shrink=.5)
widgets.interact(conditioned_marginal_contour, bandwidth=widgets.FloatSlider(min=.001,max=1.0,step=0.01,value =round(scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(sklearn.preprocessing.scale(acc),bw_method='silverman').factor,2)),C=widgets.IntSlider(min=2,max=5,step=1))

def joint_contour_conditioned(bandwidth,Orient):
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    amygdala_conditioned = amygdala[np.where(orientation==Orient)[0]]
    acc_conditioned = acc[np.where(orientation==Orient)[0]]
    amy_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amygdala_conditioned)
    acc_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(acc_conditioned)
    amy_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(amy_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    acc_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(acc_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    amy_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(amy_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    acc_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(acc_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    joint_density = np.dot(acc_kde_density[:,np.newaxis],amy_kde_density[:,np.newaxis].T)
    plt.contourf(countour_grid,countour_grid,joint_density,cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    plt.title('Joint Probablity Density Map Conditioned on Orientation = %s'%Orient)
    plt.ylabel('Acc Normalized')
    plt.xlabel('Amygdala Normalized')
    plt.colorbar(shrink=.5)
widgets.interact(joint_contour_conditioned, bandwidth=widgets.FloatSlider(min=.001,max=1.0,step=0.01,value=scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(amy_joint,bw_method='silverman').factor),Orient=widgets.IntSlider(min=2,max=5,step=1))
plt.show()

The above plots indicate some interesting relations as we can see by moving right form the first plot there is a contour that extends form the central data cloud right ward. This behavior continues until reaching the third plot or the containing on orientation 4 where we observe the most normal looking of the plots. Finally, as we move to the right most plot we observe this same appendage to the contour central plot this time extending to the left. The convergence of the direction of these appendages around the middle plots could indicate some interesting data behavior in the underlying distribution.

def error_plot_conditioned(bandwidth,Orient):
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    x_mesh,y_mesh = np.meshgrid(countour_grid,countour_grid)
    pos = np.vstack([x_mesh.ravel(),y_mesh.ravel()])
    joint_data = dual_array[np.where(orientation == Orient)[0],:]
    joint_data = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(joint_data).T
    marginal_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(joint_data,bw_method=bandwidth)
    marginal_density = np.reshape(scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(marginal_kde_obj,pos),(countour_grid.shape[0],countour_grid.shape[0]))
    countour_grid = np.linspace(start=-3.5,stop=3.5,num=200)
    amy_joint = amygdala[np.where(orientation==Orient)[0]]
    acc_joint = acc[np.where(orientation==Orient)[0]]
    amy_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(amy_joint)
    acc_joint = sklearn.preprocessing.scale(acc_joint)
    amy_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(amy_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    acc_kde_obj = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde(acc_joint,bw_method=bandwidth)
    amy_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(amy_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    acc_kde_density = scipy.stats.gaussian_kde.evaluate(acc_kde_obj,countour_grid)
    joint_density = np.dot(acc_kde_density[:,np.newaxis],amy_kde_density[:,np.newaxis].T)
    error_density = np.absolute(marginal_density - joint_density)
    plt.contourf(countour_grid,countour_grid,error_density,cmap=cm.coolwarm)
    plt.title('Error Density Map Conditioned on Orientation = %s'%Orient)
    plt.ylabel('Acc Normalized')
    plt.xlabel('Amygdala Normalized')
    plt.colorbar(shrink=.5)

The error plots above unsurprisingly each display a lack of data normality independence and unimodality regardless of bandwidth or conditioning impacts. However, it is notable that the error plots range widely in difference with each different conditioning of orientation. We see that in the first two plots the data distributional differences between the joint distribution and the product of the marginals is confined largely to 4 high density quadrants. The orientation of 4 seems to give us the least differences in distributions but still clear demonstrates two areas of high-density difference. The final plot demonstrates some interesting structure, but it is immediately non-insightful in its current form without further context aside from the differences largely being confined to the lower right on the x axis. Collectively, each of these plots leads to some insightful analysis and insight of the data. However, that comes with a lot of subjective analyst judgements concerning graph interpretation as well as parametrization which do not necessarily have explicit grounding or interpretation. For these reasons parametric or hybrid parametric methods such as these should be approached with extreme caution and diligence. These are a group of estimators that show the "art" like nature of data analysis and also demonstrate the difficulty to strike a balance in local bias vs. global variance with both bandwidth and bin width demonstrate proxies of.
